        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Bromley Kent</placeName>
                    <date>July 27<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.—</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>On my return home yesterday I received your note of the 23<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> &amp; the copies of my article on Geology in Admiralty Scientific Manual,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> for which I am much obliged &amp; remain</p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The letter is dated ‘1859’, but it is not certain that this is in CD’s hand. The year is established by the reference to Main ed. 1859 (see n. 2, below). CD returned to Down from Moor Park hydropathic establishment on 26 July 1859 (‘Journal’; Appendix II).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD refers to Main ed. 1859. CD had contributed the chapter on geology to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2259.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Frederick William Herschel’s</ref> earlier edition of the same work, the <hi rend="italic">Manual of scientific enquiry</hi> (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 4). Herschel’s edition had been published in 1849, followed by a second edition in 1851. The supervision of a third edition was transferred to Main, who was chief assistant at the Royal Observatory and president of the Royal Astronomical Society in 1859. CD’s copy of his chapter (apparently unrevised) is in DAR 132 (7). It is separately paginated and has the title ‘Manual of geology … Extracted from the Admiralty Manual of Scientific Enquiry, third edition, 1859’. The book was published early in September (<hi rend="italic">Publishers’</hi> <hi rend="italic">Circular</hi>, 15 September 1859, p. 461).</note>
        </div>        
            
